We denoted the new tachyon by the same letter as the matrix model field since
they should be identical. However, comparing two actions metr:Stach 
and metr:Sg , we see that for this identification to be true,
one must require the vanishing of the tachyonic mass
metr:vmas 
^2=0.
This equation plays the role of an additional condition for
the equations of motion metr:eqss 
and allows to select the unique solution.
It is easy to check that the linear dilaton background
metr:solld 
G_ =_ , 2  X^1,
satisfies all these equations.
Besides, we argue that it is the unique solution of
the equations metr:eqss  and metr:vmas .
It means that for any solution of MQM restricted to
the singlet sector we always get the simplest linear dilaton background.
Since the theory metr:Seff  is a model of two-dimensional dilaton
gravity with non-minimal coupled scalar field, it is not exactly
solvable. Therefore, we are not able to prove our statement
rigorously. However, in Appendix A we show that there are no solutions
which can be represented as an expansion around the linear dilaton
background metr:solld .(Of course, this result is valid only for
the equations of motion obtained in the leading order in .
For example, the background described by the CFT metr:confstr  or even
metr:PERTS  with  corresponds
to the linear dilaton background
with a non-vanishing tachyon field. Such background
does not satisfy the equations metr:eqss .
However, it was suggested that it satisfies the exact equations
which include all corrections in . We are interested
in the existence of a dual description where the non-vanishing tachyon
vacuum transforms into expectation values of other fields.
Our results show that the curvature of the target space and the dilaton
can not be changed in the leading order in .) 

Thus, any tachyon perturbation can not modify the local structure
of spacetime. However, the found solution does not forbid modifications
of the global structure. There are, in principle, two
possibilities to change it. Either something can happen with
the topology, for example, a spontaneous compactification,
or there can appear boundaries.
We argue that just these possibilities are indeed realized in our
case.

To understand why this can happen, note that in the initial
coordinates  of MQM the metric is non-trivial, although flat.
We can represent it as
metr:mets 
G_ =e^2 g_  ,
where  is the matrix coupled with the derivatives
of  in metr:Sd , whose determinant equals .
It takes the usual form  only after
a coordinate transformation.
Under this transformation, the image of the -plane is, in general,
not the whole plane, but some its subspace. Depending on boundary
conditions, it will give rise either to a compactification, or to
the appearance of boundaries.




Target space of string theory with
integrable tachyon perturbations 


In this section we analyze the structure of the target space of
2D string theory in the presence of tachyon perturbations with
discrete momenta.
Such perturbations correspond to the admissible perturbations
of the Euclidean theory described in section 2. Nevertheless, our analysis
is carried out in spacetime of the Minkowskian signature.

The case, we consider here, was shown to be exactly integrable
and described by Toda Lattice hierarchy.
Therefore, it is possible to find explicitly the classical solution ,
playing the role of the background field in the Das-Jevicki
collective theory. Moreover, as we will show,
the integrability manifests itself at the next steps of the derivation,
what allows to complete the analysis of this case.




Background field from matrix model solution 


First, we show how the classical solution  determining the string
background can be extracted from MQM.
As it was noted, it represents the density of eigenvalues.
The latter is most easily found from the exact form of the Fermi sea
formed by fermions of the MQM singlet sector.
To see how this works,
let us introduce the left and right moving chiral
fields:
metr:chf 
p_(x,t) = _x(x,t).
They have the following Poisson brackets
metr:Ppp 
p_(x),p_(y)=2_x(x-y)
and bring the Hamiltonian to the form
metr:Hampp 
H_coll =dx2  ( 16  (p_+^3-p_-^3)+
(u(x)+)(p_+-p_-) ).
Using metr:Ppp , it is easy to show that
they should satisfy the Hopf equation
metr:Hopfeq 
_t p_+p__x p_+_x u(x)=0.
This equation is of integrable type and much easier to solve than
eq. metr:Leq . The key observation, which establishes the contact
with MQM, is that in the quasiclassical limit 
determine the upper and lower boundaries of the Fermi sea in
the phase space.
Then the density is given by their difference what
agrees with the definition metr:chf .


For general integrable tachyon perturbations, the solution for
the profile of the Fermi sea has been found in.
