Flat coordinates 


We know from section 4 that any background
described by the Das-Jevicki effective action
leads to the flat target space metric. However, as we discussed above,
the global structure of the target space can differ
from that of the usual Minkowski space.
To find whether this is the case, one should investigate
the coordinate transformation mapping the target space metric
into the standard form .

In general, it is quite a difficult problem to find such a map explicitly.
Remarkably, in our case given by the solution metr:SLbac ,
this task can be accomplished.
Indeed, we show in Appendix B that the
change of coordinates from  to  with
metr:flcor 
+2 , 2 
brings the action metr:Sdfpp  to the standard form
metr:Sdffl 
S_(2) =dd
[(_)^2-(_)^2],
where the sign is determined by the sign of the Jacobian of
the coordinate transformation metr:flcor .
The Jacobian is defined by the function  in (B.2) and can
be represented in the form
metr:Jac 
2D= 2(p-)( ,
where  and
 given explicitly in (B.4).

The zeros of the Jacobian show where the map metr:flcor  is degenerate.
All multipliers in metr:Jac  vanish at
the line defined by the condition
 or ,
which corresponds to the most left point of the Fermi sea where
two branches of  meet each other (see fig. 1).
In terms of the flat coordinates
metr:flcor , this line is given in the following parametric form
metr:singl 
where  is a solution of the above condition.
Also it defines the limiting value of the coordinate , which
should always be larger than . However,
the spacetime can be
analytically continued through this line. This analytical continuation
corresponds to that
in all integrals  should run from  to  and return back
with simultaneous interchanging the roles of  and .
This shows that it is more natural to consider the plane of 
as the starting point rather than .
The former is a two-sheet cover of the physical region of the latter.
 appears as a parameter
along fermionic trajectories and it should not be restricted
to a half-line. Thus, we incorporate the whole scattering picture
and glue two copies of the resulting flat spacetime together
along the line metr:singl .

Unfortunately, there is an ambiguity in the choice of coordinates
where the action has the form metr:Sdffl .  Any conformal change
of variables metr:flcor 
metr:confch 
(,)(u(t-),v(t-))
leaves the action unchanged.  Due to this we can find the form of the
resulting spacetime only up to the conformal map. However, one can
reduce the ambiguity imposing some conditions on the map
metr:confch . First of all, it should be well defined on the
subspace which is the image of the -plane under the map
metr:flcor , that is the functions  and  should not have
singularities there.  The next condition is the triviality of
metr:confch  in the absence of perturbations since in this limit
metr:flcor  reduces to the well known transformation giving the
flat Minkowski space.  Besides, we would like to
retain the symmetry  which is explicit
when there are no phases  in
metr:SLbac . It reflects the fact the
our spacetime is glued from two identical copies (see discussion in the
previous paragraph). This leads to the condition that  and  are
odd functions.

As a byproduct of our analysis we obtain also
the conformal factor  appearing in metr:mets .
